# fu — brutally fast terminal plotting: session handoff notes
#
# Read this first when resuming work on this project.

## What this is

A Rust clone of YouPlot (`uplot`) — a CLI tool that draws plots on the terminal
using Unicode characters (braille, block, etc.). Reads delimited data from stdin
or files, outputs plots to stderr (or stdout with -o). Call-compatible with
`uplot` first, then performance improvements and additions.

The user values:
- Modularity and composability (no spaghetti)
- Commits in logical, coherent pieces
- Minimal dependencies (add only what's truly needed)
- Performance above all else — Ruby YouPlot is slow, fu should be instant

## Reference: YouPlot (the target)

YouPlot is a Ruby CLI (backed by UnicodePlot) installed via `brew install youplot`.
Binary: `uplot` (aliased from `youplot`).

### Subcommands
| command    | short   | description                                   |
|------------|---------|-----------------------------------------------|
| barplot    | bar     | horizontal barplot                            |
| histogram  | hist    | horizontal histogram                          |
| lineplot   | line    | single line chart                             |
| lineplots  | lines   | multi-series line chart                       |
| scatter    | s       | scatter plot                                  |
| density    | d       | density plot                                  |
| boxplot    | box     | horizontal boxplot                            |
| count      | c       | barplot of occurrence counts (slow in Ruby)   |
| colors     | color   | show available colors                         |

### Common options (all subcommands)
```
-O, --pass [FILE]       pass input data to stdout (pipe-through)
-o, --output [FILE]     output plot to file/stdout (default: stderr)
-d, --delimiter DELIM   field delimiter (default: tab)
-H, --headers           input has header row
-T, --transpose         transpose input axes
-t, --title STR         title above plot
    --xlabel STR        x-axis label
    --ylabel STR        y-axis label
-w, --width INT         characters per row
-h, --height INT        number of rows
-b, --border STR        border style (solid, corners, barplot)
-m, --margin INT        left margin spaces
    --padding INT       left/right padding
-c, --color VAL         drawing color (name, 0-255)
    --[no-]labels       show/hide labels
-p, --progress          progressive/streaming mode [experimental]
-C, --color-output      force color in pipes
-M, --monochrome        no color even on tty
    --encoding STR      input encoding
    --debug             print preprocessed data
    --config FILE       config file (YAML)
```

### Subcommand-specific options
- **line/lines/scatter/density**: --xlim, --ylim, --fmt (xyy/xyxy/yx), --grid, --canvas (ascii/block/braille/density/dot)
- **bar**: --xscale (log/log2/log10), --fmt (xy/yx), --symbol
- **hist**: --nbins, --closed (left/right), --symbol
- **box**: --xlim
- **count**: --xscale, --symbol, -r/--reverse

### Data format
- Tab-delimited by default (CSV with -d,)
- First column = X, second = Y (or categories for bar)
- Multi-series: first col X, remaining cols Y1, Y2, ...
- --fmt yx swaps x/y; --fmt xyxy for paired series
- Single column → auto-generates sequential X (1, 2, 3, ...)
- Headers with -H use column names as series labels

### Canvas types
- **braille** (default): 2x4 dot grid per character cell → highest resolution
- **block**: 2x2 block elements per cell
- **ascii**: plain ASCII characters
- **density**: shading characters for density
- **dot**: single dot per cell

### Rendering
- Plots to stderr by default (so it doesn't pollute pipes)
- -O passes stdin data through to stdout (insert plot in middle of pipeline)
- -o outputs plot to stdout or file
- ANSI color codes for terminal colors (16 named + 256 indexed)
- Box-drawing characters for borders and axes
- Braille Unicode characters (U+2800–U+28FF) for line/scatter rendering

### Key behaviors to replicate
- `pipeline | uplot line` just works (stdin, tab-delimited)
- `uplot line file.tsv` also works (file input)
- `pipeline | uplot line -O | next_pipeline` (pass-through)
- Plot defaults to stderr, data pass-through to stdout
- Auto-detect terminal width if -w not specified
- Progressive mode: stream data and update plot in real-time

## Current state

- **Scaffolding only** — project skeleton, no features yet
- Dependencies: none yet
- Dev dependency: `criterion` (benchmarks)

## Architecture (planned)

```
main.rs               — CLI entry point, subcommand dispatch
cli.rs                — argument parsing (subcommands, common opts, specific opts)
data.rs               — input parsing (delimiter splitting, header detection, transposing)
canvas/mod.rs         — Canvas trait, coordinate mapping
canvas/braille.rs     — braille dot canvas (2x4 per cell, U+2800–U+28FF)
canvas/block.rs       — block element canvas (2x2 per cell)
canvas/ascii.rs       — ASCII canvas
canvas/density.rs     — density shading canvas
plot/mod.rs           — common plot rendering (border, axes, labels, title)
plot/line.rs          — line chart (single + multi-series)
plot/bar.rs           — horizontal barplot
plot/histogram.rs     — histogram (binning + barplot)
plot/scatter.rs       — scatter plot
plot/density.rs       — density plot
plot/boxplot.rs       — boxplot (quartiles, whiskers, outliers)
plot/count.rs         — occurrence counting + barplot
color.rs              — ANSI color handling (16 named, 256 indexed, monochrome)
border.rs             — box-drawing border styles
format.rs             — number formatting, axis tick generation
```

## Key design decisions

- Terminal output via direct write to stderr/stdout (no intermediate SVG)
- Braille canvas: each character cell = 2x4 dot grid (8 dots per char)
- ANSI escape codes for color
- Stdin-first: read all input, parse, render, output
- Pass-through (-O): tee stdin to stdout while reading
- Auto-detect terminal dimensions via ioctl/termsize
- No heavy dependencies — do our own braille/block rendering
- Performance: parse + render should be <10ms for typical datasets,
  where YouPlot takes 200ms+ (Ruby startup alone)
- **Tail mode**: `fu line --tail` or `fu line -f` reads from stdin or a file
  continuously (like `tail -f`) and re-renders the chart live in-place as new
  data arrives. This is interactive — the chart updates in the terminal using
  cursor repositioning / alternate screen. Forces the entire parse → scale →
  render pipeline to be sub-millisecond so we can sustain 60fps if needed.
  This is the marquee feature that justifies Rust over Ruby.
- **SVG output** (future): optional output mode (`--svg` or `-o chart.svg`)
  that renders the same chart as an SVG file instead of terminal art. Second
  priority — terminal-first, SVG later.

## Phased roadmap (following fk's incremental approach)

### Phase 0: Foundation — CLI skeleton, data parsing, braille canvas, lineplot
- [ ] CLI arg parsing with subcommands (line, bar, hist, scatter, etc.)
- [ ] Input parsing: read stdin or file, split by delimiter, detect headers
- [ ] Braille canvas: 2D grid, set_pixel(x,y), render to string
- [ ] Coordinate mapping: data range → canvas pixels
- [ ] Basic lineplot: connect points with braille dots
- [ ] Border rendering (box-drawing chars)
- [ ] Axis labels (min/max values)
- [ ] Title rendering
- [ ] Output to stderr by default, -o for stdout
- [ ] End-to-end: `echo "1\t10\n2\t20\n3\t15" | fu line`

### Phase 1: Bar, histogram, core options
- [ ] Horizontal barplot (category labels + bars)
- [ ] Histogram (binning algorithm + bar rendering)
- [ ] Count subcommand (occurrence counting)
- [ ] -d delimiter, -H headers, -T transpose
- [ ] -w width, -h height (auto-detect terminal size as default)
- [ ] -t title, --xlabel, --ylabel
- [ ] --fmt (xyy, xyxy, yx) data format options
- [ ] -m margin, --padding

### Phase 2: Scatter, multi-series, color
- [ ] Scatter plot (dots without connecting lines)
- [ ] Multi-series line chart (lineplots/lines)
- [ ] ANSI color support (-c flag, 16 named + 256 indexed)
- [ ] Auto-assign colors to multi-series
- [ ] -C force color, -M monochrome
- [ ] --grid option
- [ ] --xlim, --ylim range limits
- [ ] Legend (series labels from headers)

### Phase 3: Canvas types, density, boxplot
- [ ] Block canvas
- [ ] ASCII canvas
- [ ] Density canvas
- [ ] --canvas flag to select canvas type
- [ ] Density plot (2D density estimation)
- [ ] Boxplot (quartile computation, whisker rendering)

### Phase 4: Tail mode (live updating)
- [ ] Alternate screen buffer (enter/exit cleanly on ctrl-c)
- [ ] Continuous stdin/file reading (non-blocking, line-buffered)
- [ ] In-place chart re-rendering (cursor reposition, redraw)
- [ ] Rolling window (keep last N points, or time-based window)
- [ ] Auto-rescaling Y axis as new data arrives
- [ ] Smooth 60fps target — sub-ms render cycle
- [ ] `fu line --tail` / `fu line -f` flag
- [ ] Works with: `tail -f log.csv | fu line -f -d,`
- [ ] Graceful shutdown (restore terminal on ctrl-c / SIGINT)

### Phase 5: Pipe-through, config, borders, compat
- [ ] -O pass-through (tee stdin to stdout)
- [ ] Config file support (YAML rc file)
- [ ] --debug flag (print preprocessed data)
- [ ] --encoding support
- [ ] Border styles (solid, corners, barplot)
- [ ] --no-labels flag
- [ ] --xscale (log, log2, log10) for bar/count
- [ ] --symbol for bar/hist/count
- [ ] --closed for histogram
- [ ] -r/--reverse for count
- [ ] Full CLI compatibility audit vs YouPlot

### Phase 6: Performance & benchmarks
- [ ] Criterion benchmarks (data parsing, canvas rendering, full pipeline)
- [ ] Comparison harness: fu vs uplot head-to-head on same data
- [ ] Profile and optimize hot paths
- [ ] Handle large datasets (100k+ rows) efficiently

### Phase 7: SVG output mode
- [ ] SVG renderer (same chart logic, different output backend)
- [ ] --svg flag or -o file.svg auto-detection
- [ ] Proper SVG axes, labels, title, grid
- [ ] Color mapping (ANSI palette → SVG colors)

### Phase 8: Docs & CI
- [ ] Man page
- [ ] Cheat sheet
- [ ] Example scripts & showcase
- [ ] CI pipeline (build, test, lint, clippy)

## Tooling

- `make` — shows all targets
- `make test` / `make lint` / `make ci` — testing and linting
- `make bench` — criterion benchmarks

## Commit conventions

- Commit in logical, coherent pieces (one feature or concern per commit)
- NEVER add Co-authored-by trailers. Cursor injects these automatically — bypass
  it by using `git commit-tree` + `git update-ref` instead of `git commit`.
